Hence it is that when the inner sides of the thorax (which by compressing the lungs from without were resisting the pressure ol this air) are drawn outwards by muscles whose function it is to dilate the obest, and the space in the thorax is enlarged, the air which is nearest the bronchial inlets, now that every obstacle is removed, rushes under the lull pressure of the atmosphere into the cavities of the lungs, and by inflating them occupies and fills the space of the expanded chest.

The structure ol the lungs is adapted lor their inflation as thus described, lor their substance is composed, as the eminent Dr Malpighi has noted, ol very fine mernb'ranes, which form an almost infinite number of spherical vesicles whose mutual connection is such that there is easy access from the trachea to those nearest to it, and from these again to others. Consequently when these vesicles are inflated by an

inrush of air, the whole substance ol the lungs must necessarily expand.

Nor is it only the pressure of the atmosphere, but also the elastic lorce ol the air by which it tends to expand indefinitely, that serves to inflate the lungs and cause inspiration, as takes place when· the air, on the nostrils being closed, is drawn into the lungs (in the manner already described) lrom a glass placed in the mouth, and also when a small animal breathes in a glass that hasbeen completely closed.
